<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text"><i>Larrea tridentata </i>is poorly adapted to fire because of its limited sprouting ability and resinous foliage, which is highly flammable (Marshall 1995b). Even light intensity fires can cause almost 100% mortality (Brown and Minnich 1986). Recent invasions of non-native grasses into California’s deserts have increased fire frequencies and have led to the destruction and degradation of large areas of this alliance, particularly in the western Mojave and Colorado deserts. Although thought of as a natural exclusionary process in desert grasslands of the southwest (Marshall 1995b), fire destabilizes stand dynamics in the wetter, cooler range of the species where stands have historically lacked fire. This alliance is less common and less diverse than other alliances where <i>L. tridentata </i>is a co-dominant. The presence of this alliance can indicate a disturbance history that degrades stands of the more modal <i>Larrea tridentata-Ambrosia dumosa </i>alliance. In contrast, open stands of large individual shrubs of <i>L. tridentata </i>that occupy sandy expanses do not carry fires.</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
		<tr>
			<td class="key">Fire return interval</td>
