    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Colorado Desert</b> (322Ca-d). Pure stands occupy silty basins and wash terraces with <i>Atriplex polycarpa</i> in Anza-Borrego Desert State Park and in the Ocotillo Wells State Vehicular Area (Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b). Sandy stands exist on stabilized parts of the Algodones Dunes; and others cover the bajadas, hillsides, and dune lands in the Coachella Valley (McHargue 1973).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Aa-p). Some stands are greatly degraded and are the result of the combined effects of fire, grazing, military operations, and ORV activities (Davidson and Fox 1974, Randall 1972). Other intact stands occur on sandy soils and desert pavement, some with a well-developed cryptogam layer (Evens and Hartman 2007). Stands occur at Twentynine Palms Marine Corps Base (Minnich et al. 1993), Death Valley (Annable 1985, Peterson 1984a), and generally for eastern and southern subsections (Thomas et al. 2004, Keeler-Wolf et al. 2005).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sonoran Desert</b> (322Ba-e). Stands with desert pavement are common in the Chocolate Mountains (Evens and Hartman 2007), and they are likely to occur across the section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fc-f). Stands occur at the lower elevations and in intermountain basins such as Eureka Valley and Saline Valley (Thomas et al. 2004).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bi, Bp). Upper elevation stands in Anza- Borrego Desert State Park on fine silts associate with low-alkalinity playas (e.g., Blair Valley). Some stands may have had substantial grazing in the past. Others occur in the Little San Bernardino-Bighorn Mountains region (Evens and Hartman 2007).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> In many settings, the alliance indicates prolonged burro or livestock grazing, mechanical disturbance by vehicles, or perhaps prolonged drought. Other stands in a more natural state occupy stabilized dunes and desert pavement. Prolonged drought may account for the simple stands on rocky slopes or with desert pavements. </div>
</div>

    

    

